A '''Business Architect''' is anyone who takes a step back, looks at the way work is being directed and accomplished, and identifies, designs and oversees the implementation of improvements that are harmonious with the nature and strategy of the organization.

You could say that a Business Architect is to a business what a Project Manager is to a project. Business Architects are becoming COO/CEO-level reports that address the form and structure of the organization as a whole.  They work to ensure it is optimally configured to succeed in its marketplace against its competitors using its strategy.

Business Architect training is essential for anyone who will be assuming a cross-organizational role, whether working on enterprise-wide projects or participating in corporate leadership activities. --[[User:Paul A Bodine|Paul A Bodine]] 16:36, 25 February 2006 (UTC)


